.TH "TOGGLEEVENT.SOURCE" "3JS" "October 28, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
ToggleEvent.source \- ToggleEvent: source property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]source\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]ToggleEvent\f[R] interface is an \f[CR]Element\f[R] object
instance representing the HTML popover control element that initiated
the toggle.
.SH VALUE
An \f[CR]Element\f[R] object instance, or \f[CR]null\f[R] if the popover
was not activated by a control element.
.SH DESCRIPTION
A \f[CR]<button>\f[R] element can be set as a popover control by
specifying the \f[CR]id\f[R] of the popover element in its
\f[CR]commandfor\f[R] or \f[CR]popovertarget\f[R] attribute (if the
button is specified using \f[CR]<input type=\(dqbutton\(dq>\f[R], only
the \f[CR]popovertarget\f[R] attribute works).
.PP
When the \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event fires on the popover, the
\f[CR]ToggleEvent\f[R] event object\(cqs \f[CR]source\f[R] property will
then contain a reference to the popover control button that initiated
the toggle.
This is useful for running different code in response to the
\f[CR]toggle\f[R] event depending on which popover control initiated it
(see an example).
.PP
Before the \f[CR]source\f[R] property existed, you had to manually
reimplement the \f[CR]command\f[R] attribute functionality in JavaScript
to provide a similar identifier and then monitor it to identify which
button invoked the popover.
In addition, there was a danger of such JavaScript tasks blocking the
showing or hiding of the popover.
The \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event is asynchronous, and therefore avoids this
problem.
.PP
If the popover element is not activated by a control button \(em for
example, if it\(cqs controlled using a JavaScript method such as
\f[CR]HTMLElement.togglePopover()\f[R] \(em the \f[CR]source\f[R]
property is \f[CR]null\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic \f[CR]source\f[R] usage
This demo shows how to use the \f[CR]source\f[R] property to perform
different actions based on the control button that closes the popover
element.
.SS HTML
Our markup contains a \f[CR]<button>\f[R], a \f[CR]<p>\f[R], and a
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element.
The \f[CR]<div>\f[R] is designated as an \f[CR]auto\f[R] popover, and
the button is designated as a control for showing the popover using the
\f[CR]commandfor\f[R] and \f[CR]command\f[R] attributes.
The popover contains a heading asking the user if they would like a
cookie, and two buttons labeled \f[B]Yes\f[R] and \f[B]No\f[R] allowing
them to select an answer.
Each of these buttons is designated as a control for hiding the popover.
.IP
.EX
<button commandfor=\(dqpopover\(dq command=\(dqshow\-popover\(dq>
  Select cookie preference
</button>
<p id=\(dqoutput\(dq></p>
<div id=\(dqpopover\(dq popover=\(dqauto\(dq>
  <h3>Would you like a cookie?</h3>
  <button id=\(dqyes\(dq commandfor=\(dqpopover\(dq command=\(dqhide\-popover\(dq>Yes</button>
  <button id=\(dqno\(dq commandfor=\(dqpopover\(dq command=\(dqhide\-popover\(dq>No</button>
</div>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
In our script, we start off by grabbing references to the
\f[CR]\(dqyes\(dq\f[R] and \f[CR]\(dqno\(dq\f[R] buttons, the popover,
and the output \f[CR]<p>\f[R].
.IP
.EX
const yesBtn = document.getElementById(\(dqyes\(dq);
const noBtn = document.getElementById(\(dqno\(dq);
const popover = document.getElementById(\(dqpopover\(dq);
const output = document.getElementById(\(dqoutput\(dq);
.EE
.PP
We\(cqve added feature detection for the HTML \f[CR]command\f[R]
attribute and the \f[CR]source\f[R] property.
If either is not supported in the browser, we print a message in the
\f[CR]<p>\f[R] element.
If both are supported, we add a \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event listener to the
popover element.
When the event fires, the code checks if the \f[CR]\(dqyes\(dq\f[R] or
\f[CR]\(dqno\(dq\f[R] button was used to toggle (hide) the popover
element; an appropriate message is printed to the output \f[CR]<p>\f[R]
in each case.
.IP
.EX
if (yesBtn.command === undefined) {
  output.textContent = \(dqPopover control command attribute not supported.\(dq;
} else {
  popover.addEventListener(\(dqtoggle\(dq, (event) => {
    if (event.source === undefined) {
      output.textContent = \(dqToggleEvent.source not supported.\(dq;
    } else if (event.source === yesBtn) {
      output.textContent = \(dqCookie set!\(dq;
    } else if (event.source === noBtn) {
      output.textContent = \(dqNo cookie set.\(dq;
    }
  });
}
.EE
.SS Result
